# Content System Principles (Hotel Sites)

**Inversion (what kills repeatability at scale):** inconsistent schemas, uncontrolled components, messy relationships, ad-hoc per-dev decisions. These rules **eliminate those failure modes** with minimal overhead.

Before adding patterns or new rules: *Does this reduce inconsistency? Help juniors avoid mistakes? Apply across hotel projects?* If not, skip (YAGNI: no i18n, RBAC, or workflow rules until needed).

## 1. Schema versioning

Every content structure (sections, shared entities) must include a **version** so old pages do not break silently when shapes evolve.

```js
{ type: "hero", version: 1, data: { /* ... */ } }
```

## 2. No implicit data assumptions

UI must not assume fields exist or are correctly typed. Validate in adapters or use safe fallbacks—never raw `data.title.toUpperCase()` without guards.

## 3. Required vs optional (per section)

Each section type documents an explicit contract, e.g. **Hero**: `title` (required), `subtitle` (optional), `cta` (optional). Enforce at adapter/normalization, not only in docs.

## 4. One source of truth per entity

Room, amenity, rate plan, etc. live in **one** canonical place. Do not duplicate the same entity payload across pages or JSON files.

## 5. Relationships over duplication

Repeatable domain data is **referenced by id** (or stable key), not copied inline.

```js
// ❌ Duplicated blobs per room
room: { name: "Deluxe", amenities: [{ id: "wifi", title: "WiFi" }, ...] }

// ✅ References resolve to shared records
room: { name: "Deluxe", amenity_ids: ["wifi", "tv"] }
```

## 6. Component ownership (strict layers)

- `components/blocks` (or equivalent) → CMS-driven sections only
- `components/base` → UI primitives
- `components/layout` → shells, grids, page chrome

Blocks are not base primitives; do not mix responsibilities across layers.

## 7. No inline layout in pages

Pages **orchestrate** data and section order. Grid columns, major spacing, and responsive layout belong in blocks/layout components or the layout system—not ad hoc in page templates.

## 8. Controlled variants only

Section visual/behavior differences use **predefined** `variant` (or enum) values from a fixed set—no one-off “almost hero” components.

```js
{ type: "hero", version: 1, variant: "centered", data: { /* ... */ } }
```

## 9. Media standard

Pass **structured** media objects, not bare URLs:

```js
{ url, alt, width, height }
```

## 10. Slugs and naming

Slugs: **kebab-case**, stable, no spaces or random suffixes. Example: `/deluxe-king-room` ✅, `/DeluxeRoomFinal` ❌.

## 11. Performance

No data fetching inside leaf/block components. Resolve data in pages, route loaders, or composables. Avoid redundant requests and heavy work in render paths.

## 12. No hidden business rules in UI

Pricing tiers, “premium” badges, eligibility, etc. belong in **adapters/composables** (or server). UI only renders flags/labels it receives—never `if (room.price > 5000) showPremiumBadge()`-style rules in templates.

## 13. Graceful degradation

Define defaults: fallback image, title copy, SEO fields. Missing CMS fields must **degrade** without throwing or broken layout.

## 14. CMS migration boundary

Switching local data → a headless CMS may change **only** the **data-fetching layer** and **adapters**. **Components** and **pages** stay stable when normalized contracts are unchanged—no vendor field names or response shapes outside adapters.

## Out of scope (unless product asks)

Multi-language, roles/permissions, and complex editorial workflows—add rules when there is a real requirement.
